fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Suppose that f : A \to B is a function. Then for any x, y : A there is an operation ap_{f} : (x =_{A} y) \to (f(x) =_{B} f(y)).
Moreover, for each x : A we have ap_{f}(refl_{x}) \equiv refl_{f(x)}
The notation ap_{f} can be read as the application of f to a path, or as the action on paths of f.
It suffices (by induction) to define ap_{f}(refl) :\equiv refl_{f(x)} : f(x) = f(x)
The claim is that functions behave "functorially" on paths. This is equivalent to saying functions respect equality in type theory and that functions are continuous (preserve paths) in topology.

For functions f : A \to B and g : B \to C and paths p : x =_{A} y and q : y =_{A} z we have:
ap_{f}(p \bullet q) = ap_{f}(p) \bullet ap_f(q)
ap_{f}(p^{-1}) = ap_{f}(p)^{-1}
ap_{g}(ap_{f}(p)) = ap_{g \circ f}(p)
ap_{id_{A}}(p) = p

Suppose that P is a type famnily over A and that p : x =_{A} y. Then there is a function p_{*} : P(x) \to P(y).
By induction, we can assume p is refl_{x}. We can take (refl_{x})_{*} : P(x) \to P(x) to be the identity function.

We notate the type family P in which the trasport operation happens with: transport^{P}(p, -) : P(x) \to P(y)
A type family P over a type A can be viewed as a property of elements of A that holds for x if x is inhabited. Thus, transport says that properties are preserved along paths; if P holds for x, and there is a path from x to y, P holds for y. This is equivalent to saying that properties (type families) respect equality.

Transportation can also be viewed as a "path liting" operation in a fibration. We consider a type family over A to be a fibration with a base space A and fibers P(x) over each x : A. Thus, the total space of the fibration is \Sigma _{(x : A)} P(x). Fibrations have the property that given a path p : x = y in the base space and a point u : P(x) we can lift the path p to a path in the total space starting at u.

Let P : A \to \mathcal {U} be a type family over A and assume we have u : P(x) for some x : A. Then for any p : x = y, we have lift(u, p) : (x, u) = (y, p_{*}(u)) in \Sigma _{(x : A)} P(x), such that pr_{1}(lift(u, p)) = p.
Suppose f : \Pi _{x : A} P(x); then we have a map apd_{f}: \Pi _{p : x = y} (p_{*}(f(x))) =_{p(y)} f(y)
By induction, we can assume p is refl_{x}. Then, (refl_{x})(f(x)) = f(x).
The intuition is that given a section f : \Pi _{x : A} P(x) and a path p : x =_{A} y we can apply f to p and obtain a path in the total space of P over p.
